alwaysApply: true
---

This repository uses a server-first architecture built with:

Next.js App Router

Server Actions

Zod for validation

Tailwind CSS

Prisma

Auth.js (Credentials)

Agents must follow these rules when creating or modifying code.

1. Golden Rules (Always Follow)

Default to Server Components.

All mutations must use Server Actions.

All untrusted input must be validated with Zod on the server.

Never access the database or secrets from Client Components.

Follow existing project patterns — do not invent new architecture.

Make the smallest safe change necessary.

Do not refactor unrelated files.

2. Architecture Overview
   Route Groups
   app/(auth) → public auth pages
   app/(app) → authenticated application

Middleware protects (app) routes.

Folder Responsibilities
app/actions/

Single source of truth for mutations.

Agents MUST:

Place new actions here

Not create API routes unless explicitly required

features/<feature>/

Feature domain logic.

Contains:

Zod schemas

feature types

server-safe helpers

Agents MUST colocate schemas with their feature.

lib/

Shared infrastructure.

Examples:

db.ts

auth.ts

action-helpers.ts

parse/

Agents MUST NOT add feature logic here.

components/

Reusable UI.

Rules:

UI components should be mostly presentational.

Business logic belongs in Server Actions or features.

3. Server vs Client Rules
   Server Components (Default)

Allowed:

DB access

secrets

cookies

auth()

data fetching

Client Components

Allowed:

local state

event handlers

form interactions

Forbidden:

importing prisma/db

calling server-only utilities

accessing env secrets

Minimize "use client" usage.

4. Server Action Standards

All actions must:

Authenticate user via requireUser()

Authorize resource ownership

Validate input using Zod safeParse

Return standardized ActionResult

Revalidate paths intentionally

Standard Return Shape
{ ok: true, data }

or

{ ok: false, error: { code, message, fieldErrors? } }

Never throw errors for expected failures.

5. Zod Validation Rules

Every action boundary must validate input.

Schemas must live in:

features/<domain>/<domain>.schemas.ts

Agents must:

use safeParse

convert errors via zodToFieldErrors

infer types from schemas

Never manually trust FormData or JSON input.

6. Auth Rules

Auth uses Auth.js credentials provider.

Agents must:

use requireUser() in actions

enforce ownership checks:

recipe.userId === user.id

Never trust IDs from the client.

7. Database Rules (Prisma)

Allowed locations for DB usage:

Server Components

Server Actions

lib/\* server utilities

Forbidden:

Client Components

form components

All queries must be scoped to the authenticated user when applicable.

8. Recipe Parsing Security Rules

User-provided URLs are untrusted.

Agents must:

only allow http/https URLs

block localhost/private networks

fetch HTML via lib/parse/fetch-html.ts

normalize data via parse pipeline

Parsing output is NOT trusted input.
It must be validated again when saving.

9. Tailwind CSS Rules

Use Tailwind exclusively.

Agents must:

use cn() helper for class merging

avoid inline styles unless required

preserve accessibility:

labels

focus styles

semantic elements

Do not introduce new styling systems.

10. Caching and Revalidation

Agents must explicitly revalidate when data changes:

revalidatePath("/recipes")

revalidatePath(\/recipes/${id}`)`

Never rely on implicit refresh behavior.

11. Error Handling

Expected failures:

Return structured ActionResult errors.

Unexpected failures:

Log server-side and return INTERNAL_ERROR.

Never expose stack traces to the client.

12. Middleware and Route Protection

Authenticated routes live under:

app/(app)

Agents must NOT bypass middleware auth checks.

13. Performance Rules

Prefer:

Server Components

minimal client JS

small forms

Avoid:

global state libraries unless requested

heavy client dependencies

14. Dependency Rules

Agents may add dependencies ONLY if:

no native Next.js solution exists

justified in the change summary

Never introduce alternative validation libraries or styling systems.

15. Logging Rules

Allowed:

console.error("actionName", err)

Forbidden:

logging passwords

logging tokens

logging session cookies

16. Definition of Done

Before completing a feature:

Zod validation added

Auth enforced

Ownership enforced

ActionResult returned

Tailwind styles consistent

Revalidation added

No server code in client files

Seed script has been updated

17. Agent Operating Procedure (Required)

When implementing a feature:

Locate existing schema patterns.

Create or update Zod schema.

Add Server Action in app/actions.

Use Server Component for data fetching.

Create minimal Client form if needed.

Add revalidation.

Provide verification steps.

18. Security Principles

Never trust:

URLs

IDs

FormData

parsed recipe content

Always validate server-side.

19. Code Style

TypeScript strict mode

No any unless justified

Prefer small composable functions

20. Component Size and Reuse

Agents must:

Keep all components to 200–300 lines of code; split larger components into smaller, focused pieces.

Look for opportunities to reuse existing components whenever possible instead of duplicating UI or logic.

21. If Unsure

Agents must follow existing patterns instead of inventing new structure.

Consistency is more important than optimization.
